Round 4 — Leadership & Culture Fit
What happened: This was a behavioral round with a senior manager, focused on soft skills, leadership, and alignment with DoorDash’s values.

Topics Covered:

How I’ve handled conflict within cross-functional teams
Times when I took ownership beyond my scope
Experience giving or receiving critical feedback
Understanding of DoorDash's core values, like bias for action, making room at the table, and customer obsession
Thoughts on work culture, remote collaboration, and team morale
Takeaways:

Use the STAR format (Situation, Task, Action, Result) for structured answers.
Read and reflect on DoorDash’s values beforehand — they came up directly.



4. Ownership & Leadership
This was the behavioral round, still very technical in spirit.

We had stories ready in STAR format, like:

Migrating old pipelines into Airflow and Spark.
Surviving last-minute scope changes with hard deadlines.
Working with finance, infra, and product at the same time.
Mentoring juniors and setting up coding standards.
What mattered was showing impact: “cut pipeline failures by 40%,” “reduced SLA from 6h to 1h.”

Lesson: This round is less about “what did you build?” and more about “how did you lead?”



4. Ownership / Leadership
This round is all about how you lead. I shared stories from my time at Amazon and Qatar Airways:

Migrating legacy pipelines to Airflow and Spark
Dealing with last-minute scope changes and tight deadlines
Collaborating across teams (finance, product, infra)
Mentoring and standardizing DE best practices
My advice: Have 3–4 stories ready. Use the STAR format, and highlight measurable impact.
